But Dr Illunga said the new designation would change little on the ground, as Congolese medics had been treating the epidemic as an emergency for almost a year. He stressed that Goma was fully prepared for further cases of the virus following the first case in the city. And, like the WHO, he said that any restrictions on cross border travel and trade would risk deepening the crisis. It is only the fifth time that such a public health emergency has been declared. On Wednesday, WHO Chief Tedros Adhanom said: "It is time for the world to take notice."  --BBC--